1
00:00:01,869 --> 00:00:03,359
Public Television Service

2
00:00:04,037 --> 00:00:05,027
has produced the first documentary

3
00:00:05,272 --> 00:00:07,366
of Taiwan's history,

4
00:00:08,575 --> 00:00:10,566
starting from the birth
of the island to the

5
00:00:10,811 --> 00:00:12,870
end of the 20th century.

6
00:00:13,680 --> 00:00:15,671
Each episode of the documentary

7
00:00:15,916 --> 00:00:18,317
is based on factual historical events.

8
00:00:19,286 --> 00:00:20,754
Each character is

9
00:00:20,988 --> 00:00:22,922
a real person.

10
00:00:23,156 --> 00:00:24,590
Their dialogs are

11
00:00:25,192 --> 00:00:28,162
based on historical records.

12
00:00:28,462 --> 00:00:30,328
The ancestors of the
indigenous and Han people

13
00:00:30,564 --> 00:00:32,692
crossed the ocean at different times

14
00:00:32,933 --> 00:00:35,027
to arrive at this beautiful island.

15
00:00:35,269 --> 00:00:38,933
For hundreds of years,
the ancestors endured many wars,

16
00:00:39,172 --> 00:00:41,800
colonizers, and natural disasters.

17
00:00:42,042 --> 00:00:44,841
Yet the people of Taiwan persisted.

18
00:00:45,379 --> 00:00:47,939
From being poor to being wealthy,

19
00:00:48,181 --> 00:00:50,445
from authoritarian rule to democracy,

20
00:00:50,651 --> 00:00:53,621
the people of Taiwan strive
to write their own history.

21
00:00:53,854 --> 00:00:55,822
This is our ancestors' attestation,

22
00:00:56,089 --> 00:00:58,387
one filled with trials,
tribulations, and hope.

23
00:00:58,625 --> 00:01:00,855
This is our story.

24
00:01:01,528 --> 00:01:04,395
Taiwan — A People's History

25
00:01:04,798 --> 00:01:06,823
will share with the people of Taiwan

26
00:01:07,067 --> 00:01:10,093
the road taken by our ancestors and us.

27
00:01:21,415 --> 00:01:23,907
This is the first time in Taiwan

28
00:01:24,151 --> 00:01:31,353
where history is systematically

29
00:01:31,592 --> 00:01:35,051
presented to the general

30
00:01:35,329 --> 00:01:37,297
public through television.

31
00:01:37,531 --> 00:01:38,589
The general public and the viewers

32
00:01:38,832 --> 00:01:39,765
can simply watch the documentary.

33
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:40,990
They don't have to read books

34
00:01:41,234 --> 00:01:42,065
and scour through the pages.

35
00:01:42,302 --> 00:01:43,030
From the documentary,

36
00:01:43,270 --> 00:01:45,204
viewers can reflect on
what has happened

37
00:01:45,439 --> 00:01:49,034
in Taiwan over the last few
hundred years.

38
00:01:54,114 --> 00:01:56,640
We have written history of Taiwan,

39
00:01:56,883 --> 00:01:58,442
and comic books
that depict Taiwan history,

40
00:01:58,719 --> 00:02:00,619
yet there aren't any good
films on Taiwan's history?

41
00:02:00,854 --> 00:02:02,049
For that matter,

42
00:02:02,322 --> 00:02:05,155
there just aren't any films
on Taiwan's history.

43
00:02:05,525 --> 00:02:06,993
We have all read
The Indomitable Rose

44
00:02:07,227 --> 00:02:08,820
by Yang Kuei.

45
00:02:09,062 --> 00:02:10,393
In reality, the society of Taiwan,

46
00:02:10,631 --> 00:02:11,097
the island,

47
00:02:11,331 --> 00:02:13,561
is as beautiful as the rose.

48
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:16,360
We should know our history,
and face our past.

49
00:02:16,603 --> 00:02:17,502
I believe that only a people
brave enough

50
00:02:17,738 --> 00:02:20,036
to face history will have a future.

51
00:02:24,411 --> 00:02:26,311
Since it is the history
of the people of Taiwan,

52
00:02:27,447 --> 00:02:28,608
the entire history

53
00:02:29,349 --> 00:02:31,215
therefore, must start from
the creation of the world;

54
00:02:31,485 --> 00:02:33,783
it must start from prehistory.

55
00:02:34,354 --> 00:02:36,254
This will make the history complete.

56
00:02:36,556 --> 00:02:38,285
At the same time,

57
00:02:38,525 --> 00:02:40,857
this has not been done yet.

58
00:02:42,696 --> 00:02:49,864
This documentary is the first
and the most complete one.

59
00:02:54,107 --> 00:02:56,201
We decided to film the documentary

60
00:02:56,443 --> 00:03:02,212
using reenactments and
reconstructed scenes.

61
00:03:02,449 --> 00:03:04,884
Unlike others,
we will not use narration,

62
00:03:05,152 --> 00:03:08,349
interviews, photographs, and pictures

63
00:03:08,622 --> 00:03:11,819
to show history in a monotonous way.

64
00:03:12,059 --> 00:03:13,527
This part is solemn and stirring.

65
00:03:16,129 --> 00:03:17,722
For PTS,

66
00:03:18,699 --> 00:03:21,600
it accepts donations from the
government

67
00:03:22,936 --> 00:03:25,268
and the public.

68
00:03:26,606 --> 00:03:27,869
If we could

69
00:03:28,108 --> 00:03:30,270
film the documentary

70
00:03:30,510 --> 00:03:33,036
in a livelier and more touching manner,

71
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:35,146
we can enable more viewers
to understand

72
00:03:35,382 --> 00:03:37,680
the past, present,

73
00:03:37,984 --> 00:03:40,453
and future of the land we live in.

74
00:03:41,021 --> 00:03:42,250
Viewers will want to watch

75
00:03:42,522 --> 00:03:43,512
and will be moved by

76
00:03:43,790 --> 00:03:45,121
the short stories in the documentary.

77
00:03:46,193 --> 00:03:47,285
Who did what?

78
00:03:47,527 --> 00:03:49,552
Which events were triumphs
of humanity?

79
00:03:49,796 --> 00:03:51,696
Which events benefited humanity?

80
00:03:51,932 --> 00:03:53,764
These stories are real; they existed,

81
00:03:54,034 --> 00:03:56,969
and can best reach out to the viewers.

82
00:03:57,370 --> 00:03:58,166
Reading history

83
00:03:58,405 --> 00:04:01,238
is more of a rational process.

84
00:04:01,641 --> 00:04:02,733
But when I was filming
the documentary,

85
00:04:02,976 --> 00:04:05,570
history needed to be slowly
digested and ruminated.

86
00:04:05,812 --> 00:04:08,679
History is definitely about perception.

87
00:04:09,816 --> 00:04:13,309
I think PTS must have
accomplished something,

88
00:04:13,587 --> 00:04:14,645
something important and good.

89
00:04:25,866 --> 00:04:27,857
During the Japanese occupation,

90
00:04:28,101 --> 00:04:29,535
there was an official,

91
00:04:29,770 --> 00:04:32,137
Goto Shimpei, who was also a doctor.

92
00:04:32,405 --> 00:04:35,636
He wanted to correct

93
00:04:35,876 --> 00:04:38,174
some of the hygienic habits
of the local people.

94
00:04:38,545 --> 00:04:41,037
So he came up with an

95
00:04:41,281 --> 00:04:43,113
action slogan:

96
00:04:43,383 --> 00:04:45,818
“Beat the bed sheet, clean the kitchen”

97
00:04:46,453 --> 00:04:49,514
“Beat the bed sheet, clean the kitchen”

98
00:04:49,790 --> 00:04:52,157
He hoped that the campaign

99
00:04:52,392 --> 00:04:53,985
would make the local people,

100
00:04:54,461 --> 00:04:55,986
clean up and sanitize

101
00:04:56,229 --> 00:04:58,596
their household.

102
00:04:58,832 --> 00:04:59,799
Every month,

103
00:05:00,066 --> 00:05:02,433
he would find a day
to talk with everyone

104
00:05:02,669 --> 00:05:04,763
and promote his campaign.

105
00:05:05,005 --> 00:05:06,200
As a result, since then,

106
00:05:06,439 --> 00:05:09,966
“cleaning” was referred
to as pa pia (working hard).

107
00:05:10,210 --> 00:05:10,733
Before that, the locals would
ask one another:

108
00:05:10,977 --> 00:05:11,967
Have you eaten?

109
00:05:12,279 --> 00:05:13,769
Later, it was changed to:

110
00:05:14,014 --> 00:05:14,947
Did you pa pia?

111
00:05:15,182 --> 00:05:15,648
After the campaign,

112
00:05:16,283 --> 00:05:17,045
Did you pa pia?

113
00:05:17,317 --> 00:05:18,443
Yes, yes, I have.

114
00:05:18,718 --> 00:05:20,413
So the phrase pa pia caught on,

115
00:05:20,687 --> 00:05:23,088
and evolved to its more
common meaning today.

116
00:05:23,323 --> 00:05:26,293
This is one explanation of
the origin of pa pia now.

117
00:05:28,328 --> 00:05:31,855
Events in Taiwan have always

118
00:05:32,098 --> 00:05:36,001
been related to world developments.

119
00:05:36,236 --> 00:05:38,170
I feel that the people here
should be more modest,

120
00:05:38,872 --> 00:05:41,273
and should see Taiwan through
the world's history.

121
00:05:41,508 --> 00:05:43,306
For instance, the 17th century

122
00:05:43,543 --> 00:05:44,408
and the 19th century were

123
00:05:44,644 --> 00:05:46,408
critical periods that shaped destiny.

124
00:05:46,646 --> 00:05:48,375
How did Taiwan gain
prominence in sea navigation?

125
00:05:48,615 --> 00:05:49,946
Because it was the era of
great sea navigations.

126
00:05:50,183 --> 00:05:52,618
Because of the East Asian trade.

127
00:05:52,853 --> 00:05:54,821
Taiwan was located in a trade hub;

128
00:05:55,055 --> 00:05:58,320
its significance thus became apparent.

129
00:05:58,592 --> 00:06:00,060
I think it is more objective
to view the history of

130
00:06:00,327 --> 00:06:02,989
Taiwan from the perspective
of world history.

131
00:06:03,230 --> 00:06:05,096
There are disputes

132
00:06:05,332 --> 00:06:07,027
regarding the different versions

133
00:06:07,267 --> 00:06:09,201
of Taiwan's history.

134
00:06:09,436 --> 00:06:11,336
These disputes would make us wonder

135
00:06:11,571 --> 00:06:12,299
whether we could

136
00:06:12,539 --> 00:06:15,065
keep history as it is,

137
00:06:15,308 --> 00:06:17,106
uphold the truth as it is.

138
00:06:17,344 --> 00:06:18,402
We used this perspective

139
00:06:18,645 --> 00:06:21,205
to produce a documentary

140
00:06:21,448 --> 00:06:25,112
that is more acceptable to everyone.

141
00:06:25,385 --> 00:06:27,581
With this documentary,

142
00:06:27,854 --> 00:06:29,288
people from all walks of life in Taiwan

143
00:06:29,522 --> 00:06:30,990
will get to understand

144
00:06:31,224 --> 00:06:32,385
and identify with Taiwan.

145
00:06:32,626 --> 00:06:34,993
This is our objective.

146
00:06:35,228 --> 00:06:38,630
The documentary is not only

147
00:06:40,033 --> 00:06:43,628
for the intellectuals.

148
00:06:44,204 --> 00:06:46,229
The documentary is
for the general public.

149
00:06:47,674 --> 00:06:52,908
It is based on meticulous research.

150
00:06:53,713 --> 00:06:55,181
We have carefully
chosen the film's title.

151
00:06:55,415 --> 00:06:56,041
What name did we use?

152
00:06:56,283 --> 00:06:57,614
We used the title
Taiwan — A People's History.

153
00:06:57,884 --> 00:06:58,851
The documentary is a
history of the people,

154
00:06:59,085 --> 00:07:00,780
not the history of the rulers.

155
00:07:01,321 --> 00:07:02,811
Today, PTS

156
00:07:03,423 --> 00:07:06,586
has gathered everyone to film
the documentary.

157
00:07:07,427 --> 00:07:11,989
It is not our intention

158
00:07:12,499 --> 00:07:18,165
to whitewash history,

159
00:07:18,438 --> 00:07:22,671
to create falsehood.

160
00:07:23,944 --> 00:07:27,539
Rather, we intend to present the truth,

161
00:07:27,781 --> 00:07:31,217
to discover our self identity.

162
00:07:33,186 --> 00:07:35,154
I believe that history can be
viewed from several aspects.

163
00:07:35,422 --> 00:07:36,981
It is impossible not to
have perspectives.

164
00:07:37,257 --> 00:07:39,453
Try to factor in

165
00:07:39,693 --> 00:07:41,354
the different perspectives

166
00:07:41,594 --> 00:07:43,858
in sensitive issues.

167
00:07:44,097 --> 00:07:44,859
At least, the perspectives
must be presented.

168
00:07:45,098 --> 00:07:46,759
Only by presenting the perspectives

169
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:49,731
can history be interpreted.

170
00:07:49,970 --> 00:07:51,938
The collection of historical materials,

171
00:07:52,172 --> 00:07:52,661
their choices,

172
00:07:52,906 --> 00:07:54,169
all involve different perspectives.

173
00:07:54,407 --> 00:07:55,704
This is inevitable.

174
00:07:55,942 --> 00:07:58,570
Historical truth is very important.

175
00:07:58,812 --> 00:08:00,803
The presentation of history,

176
00:08:01,114 --> 00:08:02,411
regardless of the perspective used,

177
00:08:02,649 --> 00:08:05,880
should be based on facts.

178
00:08:06,152 --> 00:08:07,176
You want to be able to piece together

179
00:08:07,454 --> 00:08:08,922
fragments of history that will

180
00:08:09,189 --> 00:08:17,722
be truthful yet interesting
to the viewers.

181
00:08:17,964 --> 00:08:19,329
History has to be interesting

182
00:08:19,566 --> 00:08:21,830
and not biased.

183
00:08:22,068 --> 00:08:24,036
Therefore, editing becomes

184
00:08:24,270 --> 00:08:25,396
very important.

185
00:08:25,638 --> 00:08:28,073
Story telling becomes very important.

186
00:08:28,375 --> 00:08:29,069
It is not simply storytelling.

187
00:08:29,309 --> 00:08:32,973
How the history is narrated
becomes very important.

188
00:08:33,213 --> 00:08:34,408
During filming,

189
00:08:34,647 --> 00:08:37,275
I had my own perspective.

190
00:08:37,550 --> 00:08:38,108
I did.

191
00:08:38,385 --> 00:08:39,819
Filming and writing

192
00:08:40,053 --> 00:08:41,111
are different.

193
00:08:41,388 --> 00:08:42,253
During filming, of course,

194
00:08:42,489 --> 00:08:44,651
there were many ideas

195
00:08:44,924 --> 00:08:46,414
or arguments,
and everybody disagreed.

196
00:08:46,693 --> 00:08:48,161
Disagreement was not an issue.

197
00:08:48,395 --> 00:08:50,830
We could not care too much
about the consequences,

198
00:08:51,064 --> 00:08:53,965
nor could we film with
apprehensions in mind.

199
00:08:54,200 --> 00:08:54,996
Otherwise,

200
00:08:55,235 --> 00:08:56,168
we could not continue.

201
00:08:56,403 --> 00:08:57,131
Although the filming process

202
00:08:57,370 --> 00:09:00,396
was a process of serious debate,

203
00:09:01,041 --> 00:09:03,135
I felt it was worthwhile.

204
00:09:03,843 --> 00:09:05,470
Because only in this way

205
00:09:05,712 --> 00:09:07,202
could we produce

206
00:09:07,447 --> 00:09:09,006
a distinctive documentary.

207
00:09:25,131 --> 00:09:26,599
Because,

208
00:09:26,833 --> 00:09:27,925
after we

209
00:09:28,168 --> 00:09:28,930
spent so much money

210
00:09:29,169 --> 00:09:30,364
and so much time on the documentary.

211
00:09:30,603 --> 00:09:32,594
If the viewers say:

212
00:09:32,839 --> 00:09:33,305
What is this?

213
00:09:33,540 --> 00:09:34,268
So dull and boring.

214
00:09:34,507 --> 00:09:35,235
This is unacceptable.

215
00:09:47,120 --> 00:09:52,854
So, it is important not to
stress historical viewpoints,

216
00:09:53,093 --> 00:09:57,894
but to make history understandable

217
00:09:59,232 --> 00:10:00,290
and interesting.

218
00:10:00,533 --> 00:10:01,398
It should be able to attract
viewers' attention.

219
00:10:01,634 --> 00:10:02,965
I think this is the most important task

220
00:10:03,203 --> 00:10:04,568
of editing.

221
00:10:05,605 --> 00:10:06,538
I admire our director very much.

222
00:10:06,773 --> 00:10:09,174
Our script

223
00:10:09,409 --> 00:10:10,205
and our research

224
00:10:10,443 --> 00:10:12,605
contained very long explanations.

225
00:10:12,912 --> 00:10:14,573
If it were me, it would take

226
00:10:14,814 --> 00:10:18,546
me more than a year to finish
narrating all the events.

227
00:10:19,085 --> 00:10:20,143
But our director only used

228
00:10:20,420 --> 00:10:21,945
40 or 50 minutes to present the ideas.

229
00:10:22,722 --> 00:10:23,985
It is really difficult

230
00:10:24,224 --> 00:10:26,158
to tell so many stories
within 50 minutes.

231
00:10:26,392 --> 00:10:28,360
The history of Taiwan over
the past hundreds of years,

232
00:10:28,595 --> 00:10:30,529
has been one of colonization.

233
00:10:30,763 --> 00:10:32,026
Wars in Taiwan

234
00:10:32,265 --> 00:10:34,529
were unending.

235
00:10:34,767 --> 00:10:36,132
It's too bad

236
00:10:36,369 --> 00:10:38,133
that so many stories
had to be squeezed

237
00:10:38,371 --> 00:10:38,963
into a short documentary.

238
00:10:39,205 --> 00:10:39,831
Each story could very well

239
00:10:40,073 --> 00:10:43,202
be developed into a good epic film,

240
00:10:43,443 --> 00:10:45,411
an epic movie.

241
00:10:46,212 --> 00:10:48,613
One can only imagine

242
00:10:48,848 --> 00:10:51,180
the events that transpired in history.

243
00:10:52,252 --> 00:10:53,310
I wanted to

244
00:10:53,586 --> 00:10:54,519
recreate the events

245
00:10:54,754 --> 00:10:56,415
for the viewers to see,

246
00:10:57,624 --> 00:11:01,720
to understand history.

247
00:11:02,428 --> 00:11:04,453
I wanted to recreate

248
00:11:04,697 --> 00:11:06,096
the historical events.

249
00:11:06,332 --> 00:11:07,390
I wanted to use dramatization

250
00:11:07,634 --> 00:11:09,033
in my documentary.

251
00:11:09,269 --> 00:11:12,170
Characters portrayed
in the documentary

252
00:11:12,405 --> 00:11:14,533
were drawn directly from history.

253
00:11:14,774 --> 00:11:16,105
The characters narrated their

254
00:11:16,342 --> 00:11:18,401
stories as they happened.

255
00:11:18,645 --> 00:11:19,077
Stories and events about human nature

256
00:11:19,312 --> 00:11:21,007
are often touching.

257
00:11:21,347 --> 00:11:22,212
Human nature.

258
00:11:22,815 --> 00:11:25,512
During the 228 Incident,

259
00:11:25,785 --> 00:11:29,881
there were stories of locals,

260
00:11:30,156 --> 00:11:32,557
such as the Fulao or Hakka,

261
00:11:32,792 --> 00:11:36,160
or even the indigenous people
harboring mainlanders.

262
00:11:36,462 --> 00:11:40,831
There were also many locals

263
00:11:41,067 --> 00:11:41,898
who were arrested.

264
00:11:42,135 --> 00:11:43,364
However, there were one or two,

265
00:11:43,603 --> 00:11:47,130
a few mainlander officials

266
00:11:47,440 --> 00:11:52,241
who risked their life to hide the locals.

267
00:11:52,478 --> 00:11:54,276
You could not tell stories like this.

268
00:11:54,747 --> 00:11:55,839
Not because you're unwilling,

269
00:11:56,082 --> 00:11:57,641
but because you didn't have
enough time.

270
00:11:58,518 --> 00:11:59,610
I feel somewhat regretful

271
00:12:00,987 --> 00:12:02,477
that the documentary is not
long enough

272
00:12:02,755 --> 00:12:06,123
to present the people's entire history.

273
00:12:06,359 --> 00:12:07,258
For instance, Dr. Mackay.

274
00:12:07,493 --> 00:12:09,018
Dr. Mackay

275
00:12:09,262 --> 00:12:11,162
was very different.

276
00:12:11,464 --> 00:12:12,590
From his diary, you would notice

277
00:12:12,832 --> 00:12:14,766
that he was a missionary

278
00:12:15,001 --> 00:12:16,765
with a strong will.

279
00:12:17,003 --> 00:12:18,437
When he arrived in Taiwan,

280
00:12:18,671 --> 00:12:20,730
he had to teach the essence of religion.

281
00:12:20,974 --> 00:12:22,464
While he preached,

282
00:12:23,543 --> 00:12:24,806
he also learned the language.

283
00:12:25,078 --> 00:12:26,170
He was very motivated,

284
00:12:26,412 --> 00:12:29,575
which, for me, was impressive.

285
00:12:29,816 --> 00:12:33,275
He was unlike other missionaries.

286
00:12:33,553 --> 00:12:35,021
Dr. Mackay was unique.

287
00:12:35,255 --> 00:12:35,847
Because

288
00:12:36,122 --> 00:12:38,614
his motivation, I believe,

289
00:12:38,891 --> 00:12:40,086
made him exceedingly Chinese.

290
00:12:40,326 --> 00:12:44,229
He and his retinue ate
from big rice pots.

291
00:12:44,464 --> 00:12:45,761
This is the historical image that I want

292
00:12:45,999 --> 00:12:47,626
to capture in my film.

293
00:12:47,967 --> 00:12:49,867
Another example is Yu Yung-he.

294
00:12:50,103 --> 00:12:51,571
You can film how

295
00:12:51,804 --> 00:12:52,737
19th Century explorers

296
00:12:52,972 --> 00:12:54,269
discovered Taiwan

297
00:12:54,507 --> 00:12:55,474
during that time.

298
00:12:55,708 --> 00:12:56,607
Yu Yung-he viewed himself

299
00:12:56,843 --> 00:12:58,311
as a civilized person

300
00:12:58,544 --> 00:13:00,205
who had invaded an uncivilized world.

301
00:13:00,446 --> 00:13:01,277
As he moved closer to

302
00:13:01,514 --> 00:13:02,811
the end of his journey in Taiwan,

303
00:13:03,016 --> 00:13:04,780
he felt more and more ashamed.

304
00:13:05,051 --> 00:13:09,147
His so-called being civilized
was actually the opposite.

305
00:13:09,422 --> 00:13:10,787
I thought that part was amusing.

306
00:13:11,024 --> 00:13:12,389
Because I had the facts
needed to tell the story,

307
00:13:12,992 --> 00:13:15,086
during filming

308
00:13:15,328 --> 00:13:17,922
I was more concerned about the characters.

309
00:13:18,498 --> 00:13:20,023
We mentioned Yu Yung-he.

310
00:13:20,366 --> 00:13:21,663
To my mind,

311
00:13:21,901 --> 00:13:23,892
I didn't have to dwell
too much on his story.

312
00:13:24,137 --> 00:13:25,002
Yet he attracted me.

313
00:13:25,238 --> 00:13:28,902
Yu was a scholar,

314
00:13:29,142 --> 00:13:31,076
a typical Chinese scholar

315
00:13:31,311 --> 00:13:33,541
with a unique character.

316
00:13:33,780 --> 00:13:36,442
He had the character of an explorer.

317
00:13:36,816 --> 00:13:38,807
He arrived in Taiwan when
he was over 60 years old,

318
00:13:39,085 --> 00:13:41,850
and traveled from south to
north in more than 10 days.

319
00:13:42,121 --> 00:13:44,715
His willpower and enthusiasm

320
00:13:44,991 --> 00:13:47,221
attracted me.

321
00:13:57,704 --> 00:14:00,173
To produce the history of the
people of Taiwan,

322
00:14:00,406 --> 00:14:01,965
to reconstruct such huge
events in history,

323
00:14:02,208 --> 00:14:04,267
there were indeed so many challenges.

324
00:14:04,510 --> 00:14:05,272
I was impressed

325
00:14:05,511 --> 00:14:08,071
by our production team.

326
00:14:08,548 --> 00:14:10,880
It is very difficulty to find

327
00:14:11,084 --> 00:14:13,746
a suitable team with
cooperative members.

328
00:14:14,020 --> 00:14:15,385
I recall that during the process,

329
00:14:15,621 --> 00:14:17,680
there were at least two major

330
00:14:17,957 --> 00:14:20,654
reorganizations in the team
of scriptwriters and directors

331
00:14:20,893 --> 00:14:22,588
due to budget constraints.

332
00:14:22,829 --> 00:14:24,991
We spent NT$5 million per episode

333
00:14:25,231 --> 00:14:26,426
to reconstruct the historical events.

334
00:14:26,666 --> 00:14:27,758
Except for Episode 2

335
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:29,092
which took place
during the 17th Century,

336
00:14:29,335 --> 00:14:31,235
all other episodes

337
00:14:31,471 --> 00:14:34,168
involved huge chronological leaps.

338
00:14:34,407 --> 00:14:36,774
Despite limited length of the episodes,

339
00:14:37,009 --> 00:14:37,771
there were so many reconstructions

340
00:14:38,010 --> 00:14:40,911
of props and costumes

341
00:14:41,147 --> 00:14:43,445
belonging to different
historical periods.

342
00:14:43,649 --> 00:14:44,241
In other words,

343
00:14:44,484 --> 00:14:46,816
faced with the decline of the

344
00:14:47,086 --> 00:14:50,852
movie and television markets
in Taiwan,

345
00:14:51,157 --> 00:14:53,148
I must compress tasks that

346
00:14:53,426 --> 00:14:54,120
could only be accomplished
by the movie industry

347
00:14:54,360 --> 00:14:56,658
into one that our production team

348
00:14:56,896 --> 00:14:58,887
could accomplish.

349
00:14:59,132 --> 00:15:00,395
It was a big challenge.

350
00:15:00,633 --> 00:15:03,125
Did Taiwan have any team capable of

351
00:15:03,369 --> 00:15:04,837
reconstructing the events of history?

352
00:15:07,607 --> 00:15:09,575
It was a very difficult task.

353
00:15:09,809 --> 00:15:11,903
I felt it was very difficult,

354
00:15:12,145 --> 00:15:14,170
but we were willing to try.

355
00:15:14,414 --> 00:15:21,912
I feel it was my personality.

356
00:15:22,188 --> 00:15:23,053
The more impossible it was,

357
00:15:23,289 --> 00:15:24,381
the more I wanted to do it.

358
00:15:24,657 --> 00:15:27,126
In Taiwan television,
the production of

359
00:15:27,360 --> 00:15:28,418
this documentary
is a pioneering endeavor.

360
00:15:28,661 --> 00:15:31,153
There were bigger challenges
than producing it abroad.

361
00:15:31,431 --> 00:15:33,126
First, there was a lack of experience.

362
00:15:33,366 --> 00:15:35,357
The documentary is the first

363
00:15:35,601 --> 00:15:37,228
history program in Taiwan
television the history.

364
00:15:37,470 --> 00:15:39,097
This documentary attempted
to reconstruct history.

365
00:15:39,338 --> 00:15:40,066
It was unprecedented.

366
00:15:40,306 --> 00:15:41,671
Second, budget was limited.

367
00:15:41,908 --> 00:15:42,466
Canadian televisions are able

368
00:15:42,708 --> 00:15:44,574
to produce 30-hour documentaries

369
00:15:44,811 --> 00:15:45,710
because their budget

370
00:15:45,945 --> 00:15:47,071
is not only 30 times ours,

371
00:15:47,313 --> 00:15:48,872
it's probably 300 times more.

372
00:15:49,115 --> 00:15:50,640
Budget constraints,

373
00:15:50,883 --> 00:15:52,248
lack of experience, and

374
00:15:52,518 --> 00:15:54,987
limited historical materials

375
00:15:55,254 --> 00:15:57,518
were the three limitations we faced.

376
00:15:57,757 --> 00:15:58,451
So, to produce such a documentary

377
00:15:58,691 --> 00:15:59,658
in Taiwan

378
00:15:59,926 --> 00:16:02,520
is more challenging than
doing so abroad.

379
00:16:03,563 --> 00:16:05,327
There were so much difficulties,

380
00:16:05,565 --> 00:16:07,397
much, much more.

381
00:16:07,633 --> 00:16:08,623
I believe one

382
00:16:08,868 --> 00:16:10,859
of the extreme difficulties

383
00:16:11,103 --> 00:16:13,162
was in finding filming locations.

384
00:16:13,706 --> 00:16:14,639
We knew

385
00:16:14,874 --> 00:16:19,141
that the topography in Taiwan
changes very quickly,

386
00:16:19,378 --> 00:16:21,437
and we wanted to be creative.

387
00:16:21,681 --> 00:16:23,979
Filming historical events on location

388
00:16:24,217 --> 00:16:26,584
was extremely difficult.

389
00:16:31,290 --> 00:16:35,693
The script had been reviewed
by many,

390
00:16:35,928 --> 00:16:40,331
and many historians

391
00:16:40,566 --> 00:16:42,796
contributed to the framework
of the stories.

392
00:16:43,035 --> 00:16:45,663
The preparatory work mainly
consisted of

393
00:16:45,905 --> 00:16:48,135
reconstructing historical events.

394
00:16:48,374 --> 00:16:50,900
The work of the director,

395
00:16:51,143 --> 00:16:52,110
of the artists,

396
00:16:52,345 --> 00:16:53,437
and of the entire production staff

397
00:16:53,679 --> 00:16:57,513
focused on the reconstruction process.

398
00:16:58,150 --> 00:16:59,379
To me, reconstruction

399
00:16:59,652 --> 00:17:01,586
was the most important.

400
00:17:01,821 --> 00:17:03,311
Yet reconstruction was difficult

401
00:17:03,589 --> 00:17:04,818
because Taiwan is so small.

402
00:17:05,057 --> 00:17:08,391
People and topography have changed.

403
00:17:08,628 --> 00:17:09,789
To reconstruct events, we had to

404
00:17:10,029 --> 00:17:11,793
spend more efforts in filming

405
00:17:12,031 --> 00:17:13,362
and managing things.

406
00:17:13,599 --> 00:17:15,124
That is not how he spoke.

407
00:17:15,368 --> 00:17:17,336
You cannot gesture too much.

408
00:17:17,603 --> 00:17:19,298
How missionaries talk.

409
00:17:20,573 --> 00:17:21,301
In fact,

410
00:17:21,541 --> 00:17:24,567
even anthropologists or historians

411
00:17:24,810 --> 00:17:26,209
could not tell us

412
00:17:26,445 --> 00:17:28,436
whether what we were doing
was correct

413
00:17:28,681 --> 00:17:30,171
because they themselves did not have

414
00:17:30,383 --> 00:17:32,442
reference pictures.

415
00:17:32,718 --> 00:17:34,277
So, this task of

416
00:17:34,754 --> 00:17:37,724
reconstructing historical events

417
00:17:37,990 --> 00:17:40,220
was the biggest challenge
we encountered.

418
00:17:40,493 --> 00:17:40,959
In the early stage,

419
00:17:41,227 --> 00:17:42,695
we sent people to the mainland,

420
00:17:42,962 --> 00:17:44,259
to the Fuzhou set

421
00:17:44,497 --> 00:17:47,432
to look for information on
costumes and props.

422
00:17:47,667 --> 00:17:50,534
We even looked for locations
in Southern Fukien.

423
00:17:50,770 --> 00:17:52,135
It was an arduous road.

424
00:17:52,371 --> 00:17:54,635
The original plan was

425
00:17:54,874 --> 00:17:56,137
to bring the entire team

426
00:17:56,375 --> 00:17:58,810
to the mainland to film on location.

427
00:17:59,045 --> 00:18:00,069
This was because the people

428
00:18:00,413 --> 00:18:03,178
along the coastal region

429
00:18:03,382 --> 00:18:06,750
in Southern Fukien had devoted

430
00:18:07,019 --> 00:18:09,420
more efforts to maintain
buildings and topography

431
00:18:09,655 --> 00:18:11,282
compared to Taiwan.

432
00:18:11,557 --> 00:18:13,423
In the selection of actors,

433
00:18:13,659 --> 00:18:15,559
it was also possible for us
to find actors who looked

434
00:18:15,795 --> 00:18:19,129
similar to people during the
17th and 19th centuries.

435
00:18:19,365 --> 00:18:22,300
Actors who are dark, thin,
and tough-looking

436
00:18:22,535 --> 00:18:23,434
are very difficult

437
00:18:23,669 --> 00:18:26,001
to find in Taiwan nowadays.

438
00:18:26,439 --> 00:18:28,806
No. 11 is Shih Lang, correct?

439
00:18:31,177 --> 00:18:33,612
Shih Lang's arrival in Taiwan?

440
00:18:38,584 --> 00:18:41,519
12? We are shooting 12 scenes today.

441
00:18:41,954 --> 00:18:43,012
You guys,

442
00:18:43,289 --> 00:18:44,779
you will appear in the 8 o'clock slot.

443
00:18:45,057 --> 00:18:46,525
You want me to faint?

444
00:18:46,759 --> 00:18:47,487
Why is he standing there?

445
00:18:47,727 --> 00:18:48,319
Strange.

446
00:18:49,495 --> 00:18:50,428
I think Taiwan does not have

447
00:18:50,663 --> 00:18:52,893
what it takes to film a history series.

448
00:18:54,667 --> 00:18:56,726
First, the movie industry here
is almost non-existent.

449
00:18:57,770 --> 00:18:59,568
It is thus difficult to make
history films.

450
00:18:59,805 --> 00:19:02,831
For costumes and art design,

451
00:19:03,542 --> 00:19:05,840
I feel our team is...,

452
00:19:06,078 --> 00:19:09,241
to quote program manager
Wang Ya-wei,

453
00:19:09,482 --> 00:19:10,176
it is extreme difficult

454
00:19:10,449 --> 00:19:12,213
for one company

455
00:19:12,752 --> 00:19:15,119
to do the work of an entire
movie industry.

456
00:19:16,822 --> 00:19:21,953
I believe that these issues

457
00:19:22,194 --> 00:19:24,856
can be resolved with money.

458
00:19:26,232 --> 00:19:28,030
There are also issues that
money cannot resolve,

459
00:19:28,267 --> 00:19:30,167
such as the topography.

460
00:19:30,903 --> 00:19:34,168
We wanted to film
Keelung Harbor and Tamsui.

461
00:19:34,407 --> 00:19:35,704
It was impossible

462
00:19:35,941 --> 00:19:38,035
to find a location

463
00:19:38,277 --> 00:19:41,178
that was similar

464
00:19:41,414 --> 00:19:42,210
to earlier times.

465
00:19:42,448 --> 00:19:44,940
You couldn't even find places
that were similar.

466
00:19:45,217 --> 00:19:46,309
Taiwan is this small.

467
00:19:47,119 --> 00:19:49,520
I was filming Cheng Cheng-kung

468
00:19:50,156 --> 00:19:52,250
in Kunni in Tainan.

469
00:19:52,525 --> 00:19:53,993
The Kunni of today

470
00:19:54,226 --> 00:19:56,194
no longer resembles
the Kunni of the past.

471
00:19:56,429 --> 00:19:57,863
Instead, we found some place similar

472
00:19:58,097 --> 00:20:00,259
in northern Taiwan.

473
00:20:00,499 --> 00:20:02,558
But still the similarities were limited.

474
00:20:03,436 --> 00:20:06,235
We could only shoot at certain angles;

475
00:20:06,472 --> 00:20:08,236
otherwise, viewers would notice.

476
00:20:08,474 --> 00:20:09,464
The difficulty

477
00:20:11,510 --> 00:20:12,671
lies in the setting.

478
00:20:13,045 --> 00:20:17,073
The setting was the most
serious problem.

479
00:20:17,316 --> 00:20:20,251
Even if the budget was okay,

480
00:20:20,486 --> 00:20:23,217
when you really started
to build the sets,

481
00:20:24,023 --> 00:20:25,923
you couldn't do it even
with the budget.

482
00:20:26,192 --> 00:20:27,159
The environment had changed.

483
00:20:27,426 --> 00:20:28,985
Only a few places are
suitable for filming.

484
00:20:29,361 --> 00:20:31,659
No matter how you shoot,
there are too many buildings.

485
00:20:32,798 --> 00:20:35,233
Unless you have a system like
that of Hollywood.

486
00:20:35,634 --> 00:20:37,728
You can build a large set,

487
00:20:37,970 --> 00:20:41,463
a Japanese street or an entire village.

488
00:20:42,341 --> 00:20:44,673
Only with that can you
be able to film

489
00:20:44,910 --> 00:20:48,210
locations that reflect the times.

490
00:20:48,447 --> 00:20:50,711
Things that truly reflect their
times are difficult to find.

491
00:20:50,916 --> 00:20:52,475
Often times,
you borrow a piece here,

492
00:20:52,752 --> 00:20:53,412
a piece there.

493
00:20:53,686 --> 00:20:54,152
You angle your camera
a little bit here,

494
00:20:54,386 --> 00:20:55,319
a little bit there.

495
00:21:00,559 --> 00:21:02,323
The periods we were filming
didn't have photography.

496
00:21:02,561 --> 00:21:06,896
We had to rely on limited
historical information.

497
00:21:08,234 --> 00:21:09,531
Without photographs,

498
00:21:09,769 --> 00:21:11,066
it was difficult.

499
00:21:11,303 --> 00:21:12,498
I believe

500
00:21:12,738 --> 00:21:13,864
the most difficult was,

501
00:21:14,106 --> 00:21:17,201
apart from changes in topography,

502
00:21:17,443 --> 00:21:19,138
that people had also changed.

503
00:21:20,312 --> 00:21:21,973
While I was filming,

504
00:21:22,214 --> 00:21:25,206
I wanted to shoot faces.

505
00:21:25,484 --> 00:21:28,419
I had intended to shoot the
change in the facial features

506
00:21:30,956 --> 00:21:33,448
of the different Han immigrants.

507
00:21:33,726 --> 00:21:37,162
To me, it was most interesting

508
00:21:38,430 --> 00:21:41,161
because after the Han arrived
in Taiwan,

509
00:21:41,400 --> 00:21:46,133
they underwent many
assimilations with others.

510
00:21:48,140 --> 00:21:49,130
To me, the images

511
00:21:50,142 --> 00:21:51,906
of the people of Taiwan

512
00:21:52,478 --> 00:21:57,006
attracted me more than anything else.

513
00:21:57,249 --> 00:21:59,479
But it was difficult for me to
capture these on film.

514
00:21:59,752 --> 00:22:02,187
The peoples have changed.

515
00:22:02,421 --> 00:22:03,752
They are different from
what I expected.

516
00:22:03,989 --> 00:22:05,548
Second is the reconstruction process.

517
00:22:05,825 --> 00:22:07,020
These actors have grown fat.

518
00:22:07,259 --> 00:22:08,158
None of them is skinny.

519
00:22:08,394 --> 00:22:09,862
However, there were no fat
people back then.

520
00:22:10,129 --> 00:22:10,755
It's that simple.

521
00:22:10,996 --> 00:22:12,623
So when we were screening actors,

522
00:22:12,865 --> 00:22:13,627
we had problems.

523
00:22:13,866 --> 00:22:15,664
There were too many fat actors.

524
00:22:16,535 --> 00:22:20,597
With the living conditions then,

525
00:22:20,840 --> 00:22:22,535
the people should have been skinny.

526
00:22:22,775 --> 00:22:23,640
No one was fat.

527
00:22:24,243 --> 00:22:25,938
We were almost unable to find
skinny actors.

528
00:22:26,178 --> 00:22:28,169
Even among the indigenous people,

529
00:22:28,414 --> 00:22:32,373
no one was skinny.

530
00:22:34,320 --> 00:22:37,221
The physical size of
the people have changed.

531
00:22:47,800 --> 00:22:49,825
The director had hoped

532
00:22:50,069 --> 00:22:51,468
that if the phrase pa pia

533
00:22:51,704 --> 00:22:53,934
was used as title,

534
00:22:54,173 --> 00:22:56,437
he would need a

535
00:22:56,675 --> 00:22:58,143
famous calligrapher

536
00:22:58,377 --> 00:23:01,347
or a persuasive calligrapher

537
00:23:01,580 --> 00:23:02,911
to write the characters.

538
00:23:03,182 --> 00:23:04,149
The director thought about

539
00:23:04,383 --> 00:23:08,320
inviting Tang Yang-tzu
to write the characters.

540
00:23:08,554 --> 00:23:09,919
I thought that since

541
00:23:10,155 --> 00:23:14,285
a famous calligrapher
had been invited,

542
00:23:14,526 --> 00:23:17,257
the focus could be on the manner

543
00:23:17,496 --> 00:23:19,624
in which the characters
pa pia were written.

544
00:23:19,865 --> 00:23:21,629
We could use

545
00:23:21,867 --> 00:23:23,699
the strokes of the two characters

546
00:23:23,936 --> 00:23:25,597
to bring out images
of major characters,

547
00:23:25,838 --> 00:23:27,897
or to bring out major events.

548
00:23:32,745 --> 00:23:34,474
But how do you reconstruct
the characters and events?

549
00:23:34,713 --> 00:23:36,647
Many characters and events

550
00:23:36,849 --> 00:23:39,978
were mere passages in history books.

551
00:23:40,653 --> 00:23:42,178
What images do those passages
conjure?

552
00:23:42,454 --> 00:23:43,080
With those passages,

553
00:23:43,355 --> 00:23:46,381
you need to transform them
into images and locations.

554
00:23:56,769 --> 00:23:57,429
If you merely concentrated on

555
00:23:57,670 --> 00:23:59,866
faithful reconstruction of the passages,

556
00:24:00,105 --> 00:24:01,197
I believe it would be

557
00:24:04,610 --> 00:24:08,205
less meaningful to the viewers.

558
00:24:12,418 --> 00:24:13,476
Instead, I believe in

559
00:24:14,219 --> 00:24:18,452
providing some latitude,

560
00:24:18,691 --> 00:24:19,681
because history

561
00:24:19,959 --> 00:24:24,453
is actually very romantic.

