00:24:24,697 --> 00:24:25,926
It's not to say that I did not
follow historical facts,

563
00:24:26,165 --> 00:24:29,260
nor did I present the facts
in an abstract level.

564
00:24:29,501 --> 00:24:32,664
I believe I conveyed the message.

565
00:24:33,038 --> 00:24:34,631
Not the every factual detail,
but I did convey the message.

566
00:24:34,873 --> 00:24:38,901
We conveyed the message

567
00:24:39,445 --> 00:24:42,779
and provide the viewers some latitude.

568
00:24:43,015 --> 00:24:45,006
I believe that was more important.

569
00:24:45,284 --> 00:24:48,447
For instance,

570
00:24:51,323 --> 00:24:54,418
we built a set duplicating

571
00:24:56,128 --> 00:24:58,028
the inside of Fort Zeelandia.

572
00:25:00,766 --> 00:25:03,758
We did not actually follow
the design plan.

573
00:25:05,738 --> 00:25:08,435
I thought of using lights and shadows

574
00:25:09,308 --> 00:25:13,438
and imagination

575
00:25:13,679 --> 00:25:14,339
to build the set.

576
00:25:14,580 --> 00:25:16,309
I believe the set had the right feel.

577
00:25:16,749 --> 00:25:17,739
When the viewers

578
00:25:17,983 --> 00:25:18,506
see it, they would naturally

579
00:25:18,784 --> 00:25:21,913
feel that it is right
although we did not tell

580
00:25:22,187 --> 00:25:24,212
the viewers that the feeling was right.

581
00:25:24,490 --> 00:25:25,286
It is like that.

582
00:25:25,524 --> 00:25:26,423
If we told the actors

583
00:25:27,426 --> 00:25:28,587
what were the emotions

584
00:25:28,827 --> 00:25:31,353
of the farewell scene

585
00:25:31,597 --> 00:25:34,259
we could replicate and capture
the feelings and emotions.

586
00:25:44,309 --> 00:25:46,744
You need to simulate the situation.

587
00:25:48,147 --> 00:25:50,081
Of course, you have to use
your imagination.

588
00:25:50,349 --> 00:25:52,317
If the simulated atmosphere was right,

589
00:25:52,551 --> 00:25:53,677
the emotions would be right.

590
00:25:55,854 --> 00:25:56,753
Of course, it was more difficult

591
00:25:56,989 --> 00:25:58,320
when we had to show
details of the props.

592
00:25:58,557 --> 00:26:01,390
The props would have to be
built in more detail.

593
00:26:02,628 --> 00:26:04,892
The more detail, the better the effects.

594
00:26:05,798 --> 00:26:08,290
If you could shoot on location,

595
00:26:08,534 --> 00:26:11,265
it would be the best.

596
00:26:11,503 --> 00:26:12,800
Because the set would become
more realistic.

597
00:26:13,038 --> 00:26:14,164
Even not filming inside the studio

598
00:26:14,473 --> 00:26:15,838
the set was easily controlled,

599
00:26:16,075 --> 00:26:18,476
but we needed extra efforts.

600
00:26:20,946 --> 00:26:21,538
I was most excited

601
00:26:21,780 --> 00:26:27,014
shooting the ship scene.

602
00:26:27,286 --> 00:26:28,754
I remember one time

603
00:26:29,021 --> 00:26:32,355
filming the second episode on location.

604
00:26:32,858 --> 00:26:33,984
It was the sea battle between
Cheng Cheng-kung and the Dutch,

605
00:26:34,226 --> 00:26:36,558
which was the 916 Sea Battle.

606
00:26:36,795 --> 00:26:37,887
When we were filming,

607
00:26:38,130 --> 00:26:39,222
we invited Weng Chia-yin,

608
00:26:39,465 --> 00:26:41,433
who was the advisor for Episode 2,

609
00:26:41,667 --> 00:26:42,600
to the set.

610
00:26:43,135 --> 00:26:44,694
I could see

611
00:26:45,404 --> 00:26:49,272
excitement

612
00:26:49,508 --> 00:26:51,169
written all over his face.

613
00:26:51,510 --> 00:26:55,310
Weng had visited the
Netherlands before,

614
00:26:55,547 --> 00:26:56,810
and he knew that the Dutch

615
00:26:57,049 --> 00:26:58,517
had built

616
00:26:58,784 --> 00:27:00,252
a 17th century battleship

617
00:27:00,486 --> 00:27:02,045
of the great sea navigation era.

618
00:27:02,421 --> 00:27:03,718
So, when he saw

619
00:27:03,956 --> 00:27:05,151
the ship we had built

620
00:27:05,424 --> 00:27:07,153
at the Pali set,

621
00:27:07,392 --> 00:27:08,553
he was so excited.

622
00:27:08,794 --> 00:27:10,193
Weng was a scholar.

623
00:27:10,429 --> 00:27:12,488
His research paper

624
00:27:12,731 --> 00:27:14,893
has been read, digested,

625
00:27:15,134 --> 00:27:17,364
and transformed into film.

626
00:27:17,603 --> 00:27:19,628
Excitement

627
00:27:19,872 --> 00:27:20,862
was on his face.

628
00:27:21,206 --> 00:27:22,139
The reproduction was

629
00:27:22,374 --> 00:27:24,138
more than 90 percent accurate.

630
00:27:24,376 --> 00:27:26,811
He said even the canons
looked authentic.

631
00:27:27,045 --> 00:27:29,412
I myself was also happy.

632
00:27:30,849 --> 00:27:31,839
We chatted

633
00:27:32,117 --> 00:27:33,084
with the director.

634
00:27:33,352 --> 00:27:35,411
We had given the director
some limitations.

635
00:27:35,988 --> 00:27:38,389
Then you would feel very confident

636
00:27:38,891 --> 00:27:40,689
because you wouldn't let him, say,

637
00:27:40,926 --> 00:27:42,587
he wanted to shoot a sea battle

638
00:27:42,828 --> 00:27:44,728
and he'll go all out

639
00:27:44,963 --> 00:27:47,227
filming bloody battles
in the raging sea.

640
00:27:47,466 --> 00:27:48,399
So then would you do it?

641
00:27:49,401 --> 00:27:50,095
We did not, for example,

642
00:27:50,335 --> 00:27:51,564
actually put a ship

643
00:27:51,803 --> 00:27:53,635
at sea,

644
00:27:53,872 --> 00:27:56,603
because it would be

645
00:27:57,543 --> 00:27:58,738
too difficult to do.

646
00:28:00,145 --> 00:28:01,613
It would be very difficult.

647
00:28:01,847 --> 00:28:04,509
We were not filming the Titanic.

648
00:28:04,750 --> 00:28:09,711
I believe that without

649
00:28:11,623 --> 00:28:14,285
the proper environment,

650
00:28:14,526 --> 00:28:15,049
magnifying the battle scene

651
00:28:15,327 --> 00:28:16,954
would serve no purpose.

652
00:28:17,196 --> 00:28:18,789
Yes, you would feel more restricted.

653
00:28:19,031 --> 00:28:23,593
When we were shooting
Cheng Cheng-kung's ship,

654
00:28:24,870 --> 00:28:25,769
we did it inside the studio.

655
00:28:26,004 --> 00:28:29,338
But our post-production
could not keep up,

656
00:28:30,542 --> 00:28:33,273
and we had to find out what it
was that's causing the delay.

657
00:28:33,579 --> 00:28:36,776
For the scene inside
the Dutch ship,

658
00:28:37,249 --> 00:28:38,216
although there were limitations,

659
00:28:38,450 --> 00:28:39,440
we were able to

660
00:28:39,718 --> 00:28:40,947
work around the limitations

661
00:28:41,920 --> 00:28:44,082
and come up with a complete work.

662
00:28:44,356 --> 00:28:46,017
All the details were done this way.

663
00:28:46,258 --> 00:28:52,197
I felt this was the right way,

664
00:28:52,998 --> 00:28:55,228
because you capture the exact
emotions on film,

665
00:28:55,467 --> 00:28:57,993
and we could reproduce
intricate details.

666
00:29:11,550 --> 00:29:13,382
Writers and historians

667
00:29:13,652 --> 00:29:16,781
can simply use words to
describe an epic battle.

668
00:29:17,055 --> 00:29:19,490
But in film,

669
00:29:19,725 --> 00:29:21,921
we have to use the computer

670
00:29:22,160 --> 00:29:25,061
during post-production

671
00:29:25,297 --> 00:29:27,823
to painstakingly produce

672
00:29:28,066 --> 00:29:30,763
the large-scale battles
at sea or on land.

673
00:29:39,278 --> 00:29:40,040
Also,

674
00:29:40,279 --> 00:29:43,271
the documentary is the first
in TV history

675
00:29:43,515 --> 00:29:44,880
to use movie magic,

676
00:29:45,150 --> 00:29:46,709
so producing the documentary

677
00:29:46,985 --> 00:29:49,682
in Taiwan is more challenging
than it is abroad.

678
00:30:04,336 --> 00:30:05,360
The production process

679
00:30:05,604 --> 00:30:07,402
is very complicated.

680
00:30:07,639 --> 00:30:10,301
There were in total

681
00:30:10,542 --> 00:30:13,944
close to a hundred

682
00:30:14,179 --> 00:30:16,546
special effects

683
00:30:16,782 --> 00:30:20,309
in the first four episodes.

684
00:30:20,585 --> 00:30:22,610
Some were animations.

685
00:30:23,922 --> 00:30:25,720
Hours and hours were spent

686
00:30:25,957 --> 00:30:29,757
on this difficult task.

687
00:30:30,996 --> 00:30:31,758
It was unprecedented.

688
00:30:31,997 --> 00:30:32,555
I believe there never was any

689
00:30:32,798 --> 00:30:36,132
TV program that used the same
kinds of special effects.

690
00:30:36,968 --> 00:30:38,333
In the beginning,

691
00:30:38,570 --> 00:30:39,935
due to time constraints

692
00:30:40,172 --> 00:30:41,333
and lack of experience,

693
00:30:42,040 --> 00:30:45,271
many things had yet to mesh.

694
00:30:45,510 --> 00:30:47,103
We had produced many TV ads.

695
00:30:47,412 --> 00:30:49,779
So when we relied on our experience

696
00:30:50,048 --> 00:30:51,948
to process certain special
effects details,

697
00:30:52,217 --> 00:30:55,676
we were nitpicking.

698
00:30:57,089 --> 00:31:00,081
Yet TV documentaries
do not allow you

699
00:31:00,359 --> 00:31:03,192
to work into details.

700
00:31:04,696 --> 00:31:08,792
Thus we simply did our best

701
00:31:09,034 --> 00:31:11,025
or did what was possible

702
00:31:11,503 --> 00:31:18,341
to produce something
satisfactory to us.

703
00:31:24,983 --> 00:31:27,213
Historical documentaries or

704
00:31:27,486 --> 00:31:31,423
films based on stringent research

705
00:31:31,690 --> 00:31:34,421
usually cover much serious topics.

706
00:31:34,659 --> 00:31:37,594
To us

707
00:31:37,829 --> 00:31:38,455
or to the viewers,

708
00:31:38,697 --> 00:31:40,495
these films could be boring.

709
00:31:40,732 --> 00:31:42,257
That's why the director and |

710
00:31:42,501 --> 00:31:43,969
decided to add more

711
00:31:44,202 --> 00:31:47,570
interesting animations.

712
00:31:48,073 --> 00:31:51,600
Basically, I hope each episode

713
00:31:52,377 --> 00:31:57,872
is unique in its own way.

714
00:31:58,750 --> 00:31:59,546
For instance, in the first episode,

715
00:31:59,851 --> 00:32:02,684
we focused on computer
animation and

716
00:32:02,921 --> 00:32:06,619
the realism of the evolution
of the earth.

717
00:32:06,858 --> 00:32:09,020
How did Taiwan come about?

718
00:32:23,508 --> 00:32:24,976
During our 3-D production,

719
00:32:25,210 --> 00:32:28,908
we first tried to obtain
the desired images,

720
00:32:29,147 --> 00:32:31,639
then decide how big the set would be.

721
00:32:32,551 --> 00:32:33,882
At this point,

722
00:32:34,152 --> 00:32:36,120
the models would be decided.

723
00:32:36,888 --> 00:32:38,549
We then proceeded

724
00:32:38,824 --> 00:32:40,588
to the texture of the models.

725
00:32:40,826 --> 00:32:42,453
We pasted pictures and

726
00:32:42,694 --> 00:32:44,628
manipulated the coloring effects.

727
00:32:45,797 --> 00:32:46,855
If the models

728
00:32:47,098 --> 00:32:48,930
had to be movable,

729
00:32:49,167 --> 00:32:50,498
we installed frameworks

730
00:32:50,735 --> 00:32:52,362
to provide simple movements.

731
00:32:53,271 --> 00:32:54,261
After that,

732
00:32:54,506 --> 00:32:55,337
we improved

733
00:32:56,107 --> 00:32:58,132
the image quality.

734
00:32:58,376 --> 00:32:59,172
Through a process called rendering.

735
00:32:59,711 --> 00:33:01,338
After rendering,

736
00:33:01,580 --> 00:33:03,344
if we still needed smoke and fire,

737
00:33:03,548 --> 00:33:05,277
it would be more difficult

738
00:33:05,550 --> 00:33:06,449
to create using 3-D software.

739
00:33:06,718 --> 00:33:08,015
We would use

740
00:33:08,286 --> 00:33:11,051
2-D software to provide these
special effects.

741
00:33:11,623 --> 00:33:13,091
The entire procedure involved

742
00:33:13,325 --> 00:33:15,657
modeling and texturing,

743
00:33:15,961 --> 00:33:19,022
making the images move,
and rendering.

744
00:33:19,264 --> 00:33:20,663
After rendering came integration,

745
00:33:20,899 --> 00:33:23,163
we might even add some more things.

746
00:33:23,401 --> 00:33:24,869
For example, this wall painting.

747
00:33:25,136 --> 00:33:28,970
We initially wanted

748
00:33:29,207 --> 00:33:31,642
simple lines,

749
00:33:31,877 --> 00:33:34,812
and also clearly show

750
00:33:35,046 --> 00:33:38,346
some activities of the ancient people

751
00:33:38,583 --> 00:33:45,512
in the community during that time.

752
00:33:45,790 --> 00:33:46,518
Like this,

753
00:33:49,127 --> 00:33:51,528
the human outline and

754
00:33:51,763 --> 00:33:52,389
the animation were patterned

755
00:33:52,631 --> 00:33:55,225
after the wall paintings of

756
00:33:55,467 --> 00:33:58,459
indigenous people in Europe and Asia.

757
00:33:58,703 --> 00:34:00,603
It was a combination of many things.

758
00:34:00,839 --> 00:34:04,935
We tried to imitate its style

759
00:34:05,243 --> 00:34:06,642
to create something new.

760
00:34:06,878 --> 00:34:09,870
It was just like regular graffiti.

761
00:34:10,348 --> 00:34:13,648
Because they engaged in
these activities,

762
00:34:13,919 --> 00:34:15,478
we imitated them.

763
00:34:15,754 --> 00:34:19,190
Or, we imagined what they did.

764
00:34:20,025 --> 00:34:21,083
For example, hunting

765
00:34:21,359 --> 00:34:25,557
or domesticating dogs.

766
00:34:25,797 --> 00:34:29,927
These activities were written
in historical records.

767
00:34:30,168 --> 00:34:31,294
They discovered

768
00:34:31,536 --> 00:34:34,096
skeletons of dogs,

769
00:34:34,406 --> 00:34:35,305
so we thought there must be

770
00:34:35,540 --> 00:34:39,977
dogs living with the humans.

771
00:34:40,211 --> 00:34:41,110
So we had a small dog

772
00:34:41,346 --> 00:34:42,745
running about.

773
00:34:46,017 --> 00:34:50,215
I used my imagination

774
00:34:50,488 --> 00:34:54,755
to make these serious

775
00:34:54,993 --> 00:34:59,863
and boring scenes

776
00:35:00,065 --> 00:35:01,430
a bit lively.

777
00:35:01,666 --> 00:35:05,364
It was really

778
00:35:05,604 --> 00:35:08,596
an integration of

779
00:35:08,840 --> 00:35:10,137
2D and 3D animation.

780
00:35:11,376 --> 00:35:14,038
The lines were drawn with 2D,

781
00:35:17,082 --> 00:35:21,485
then combined with the 3D mountains.

782
00:35:22,520 --> 00:35:25,490
In the second episode,
of the great sea navigation era,

783
00:35:25,757 --> 00:35:26,918
the maps were very important.

784
00:35:27,158 --> 00:35:30,560
We wanted to have different
types of maps

785
00:35:32,864 --> 00:35:35,196
because I wanted to have
different presentations.

786
00:35:35,433 --> 00:35:37,629
I wanted the indicators on the maps

787
00:35:37,869 --> 00:35:40,839
to be different from previous ones.

788
00:35:44,542 --> 00:35:46,636
The maps were very important,

789
00:35:47,178 --> 00:35:50,170
with all the countries and places.

790
00:35:50,415 --> 00:35:51,280
It was very complicated.

791
00:35:51,516 --> 00:35:51,778
For example,

792
00:35:52,050 --> 00:35:54,519
if all maps looked similar,

793
00:35:54,786 --> 00:35:56,345
it would be boring.

794
00:35:56,621 --> 00:36:00,785
The visuals would be dull.

795
00:36:01,026 --> 00:36:04,121
So I spent lots of efforts

796
00:36:04,529 --> 00:36:06,088
to highlight the maps

797
00:36:06,331 --> 00:36:08,595
yet keeping them in line with the tone.

798
00:36:17,709 --> 00:36:21,145
The third episode was more
like opera.

799
00:36:21,479 --> 00:36:22,207
It is livelier.

800
00:36:22,447 --> 00:36:24,779
The episode contained fight
scenes using weapons,

801
00:36:25,016 --> 00:36:31,149
and the scenes were more repetitive.

802
00:36:31,423 --> 00:36:35,451
The episode contained a more
serious theme.

803
00:36:35,727 --> 00:36:37,627
So how do you soften it a bit,

804
00:36:37,862 --> 00:36:39,523
and make it more digestible

805
00:36:40,031 --> 00:36:42,056
for the audience?

806
00:36:43,168 --> 00:36:46,661
I thought of making it more interesting.

807
00:36:46,905 --> 00:36:50,102
When you find something interesting

808
00:36:50,341 --> 00:36:54,369
you would unconsciously absorb
what the plot is offering you.

809
00:36:54,612 --> 00:36:58,048
I liked adding ancient

810
00:36:58,283 --> 00:37:02,447
materials in the film.

811
00:37:02,721 --> 00:37:04,883
That is, introducing

812
00:37:05,156 --> 00:37:06,715
ancient materials into

813
00:37:06,991 --> 00:37:09,551
some modern special effects

814
00:37:09,794 --> 00:37:11,319
or computer animations.

815
00:37:11,563 --> 00:37:17,161
It gave the film more of a
historical persona.

816
00:37:17,402 --> 00:37:22,533
The shadow puppet show was
an interesting performance.

817
00:37:22,774 --> 00:37:23,536
I thought

818
00:37:23,775 --> 00:37:25,539
it had artistic taste,

819
00:37:25,777 --> 00:37:27,245
design creativity,

820
00:37:27,479 --> 00:37:30,710
even creative animation.

821
00:37:30,915 --> 00:37:34,215
Initially, I wanted to invite

822
00:37:34,853 --> 00:37:36,878
a shadow puppet troupe to perform.

823
00:37:37,188 --> 00:37:42,649
But new puppets would
have to be made,

824
00:37:43,061 --> 00:37:46,463
and the script would have
to be rewritten.

825
00:37:46,731 --> 00:37:48,165
Also, the availability of the
troupe was a concern,

826
00:37:48,399 --> 00:37:50,527
so was the budget.

827
00:37:51,636 --> 00:37:53,502
Finally we decided

828
00:37:53,738 --> 00:37:55,797
that a more creative way

829
00:37:56,040 --> 00:37:59,237
would be to use animation,
which would be interesting.

830
00:37:59,477 --> 00:38:03,380
I wanted it to be slightly abstract,

831
00:38:03,615 --> 00:38:07,882
especially when I read

832
00:38:08,153 --> 00:38:09,621
the story of Chu Yi-kuei.

833
00:38:09,854 --> 00:38:12,619
I thought it was dramatic.

834
00:38:12,857 --> 00:38:14,484
Breeding ducks,

835
00:38:14,726 --> 00:38:17,423
commanding ducks to form a line.

836
00:38:17,662 --> 00:38:20,427
These were meant for film.

837
00:38:20,665 --> 00:38:21,223
If this segment were

838
00:38:21,466 --> 00:38:22,934
dramatized,

839
00:38:23,168 --> 00:38:26,160
it would become unexciting

840
00:38:26,404 --> 00:38:28,133
and difficult to film.

841
00:38:28,373 --> 00:38:29,363
Using shadow puppets might

842
00:38:29,607 --> 00:38:32,269
make it more interesting

843
00:38:32,510 --> 00:38:34,035
and lively.

844
00:38:34,279 --> 00:38:35,974
It would also attract viewers.

845
00:38:46,124 --> 00:38:47,990
Because Taiwan's history

846
00:38:48,226 --> 00:38:49,785
is dramatic.

847
00:38:50,128 --> 00:38:52,426
Using music to express

848
00:38:52,697 --> 00:38:54,062
happiness, anger, sadness, and fun

849
00:38:55,166 --> 00:38:57,157
was also a big challenge.

850
00:38:58,336 --> 00:38:59,963
Since the documentary

851
00:39:01,072 --> 00:39:04,064
involved the history of Taiwan,

852
00:39:04,309 --> 00:39:06,539
traditional Taiwanese music
first came to mind.

853
00:39:06,778 --> 00:39:09,110
Or music from the period of
Japanese occupation,

854
00:39:09,347 --> 00:39:11,338
or something similar.

855
00:39:12,450 --> 00:39:17,718
Later, I thought I should

856
00:39:17,956 --> 00:39:20,050
project my own feeling,

857
00:39:20,325 --> 00:39:21,815
because I do not want to say

858
00:39:23,027 --> 00:39:24,893
I referred to this and that,

859
00:39:26,130 --> 00:39:31,694
and then the music just came together.

860
00:39:31,936 --> 00:39:32,368
You will see,

861
00:39:32,604 --> 00:39:36,131
it is like looking at a clock.

862
00:39:36,374 --> 00:39:38,968
The dials running in the
opposite direction;

863
00:39:39,210 --> 00:39:41,338
it's the feeling of time passing.

864
00:39:45,283 --> 00:39:46,273
I felt the music was

865
00:39:46,551 --> 00:39:47,985
slightly melancholic,

866
00:39:48,219 --> 00:39:50,244
yet I did not feel

867
00:39:50,521 --> 00:39:53,252
the music was sad.

868
00:39:53,591 --> 00:39:56,253
In its melancholy,

869
00:39:56,995 --> 00:39:59,430
the music contained

870
00:39:59,664 --> 00:40:03,259
elements of hope.

871
00:40:03,534 --> 00:40:05,593
Just like when I was little,

872
00:40:05,837 --> 00:40:07,236
I would hear a melody

873
00:40:07,472 --> 00:40:08,769
or whatever

874
00:40:10,808 --> 00:40:13,368
that conjured

875
00:40:13,478 --> 00:40:17,415
past feelings.

876
00:40:18,316 --> 00:40:19,681
In fact, I started

877
00:40:19,951 --> 00:40:22,886
to identify with the melody

878
00:40:23,121 --> 00:40:25,385
when I was doing the film title.

879
00:40:26,357 --> 00:40:28,587
The music going with the film title
was the first to appear.

880
00:40:28,826 --> 00:40:32,387
I wanted strings

881
00:40:32,931 --> 00:40:35,423
because string instruments

882
00:40:35,667 --> 00:40:37,829
can better

883
00:40:38,069 --> 00:40:40,299
relate feelings.

884
00:40:45,143 --> 00:40:47,134
I cannot forget a scene

885
00:40:48,513 --> 00:40:50,982
at the end of episode six,

886
00:40:51,215 --> 00:40:58,281
where Taiwanese were turned
into Japanese soldiers.

887
00:41:03,428 --> 00:41:05,260
After Japan lost the war,

888
00:41:05,496 --> 00:41:08,693
the Nationalist government,
which was the former enemy,

889
00:41:08,933 --> 00:41:13,200
arrived in Taiwan, and soldiers
had identity crisis.

890
00:41:13,771 --> 00:41:14,465
I had strong emotions

891
00:41:14,706 --> 00:41:17,698
while filming that segment.

892
00:41:24,382 --> 00:41:26,009
Maybe it was because

893
00:41:26,284 --> 00:41:27,615
that part of history was less distant

894
00:41:27,885 --> 00:41:31,685
and I felt connected.

895
00:41:38,896 --> 00:41:44,232
Maybe it was more difficult for me

896
00:41:44,469 --> 00:41:46,494
to understand the history
of the long past.

897
00:41:46,804 --> 00:41:48,898
But the arrival of the
Nationalist government

898
00:41:49,140 --> 00:41:51,507
was the time of my grandparents.

899
00:41:55,413 --> 00:41:56,471
The accompanying music

900
00:41:58,116 --> 00:41:59,982
was actually very simple.

901
00:42:00,251 --> 00:42:01,514
It was very simple.

902
00:42:03,521 --> 00:42:07,856
But I believe that
the simpler a music is,

903
00:42:09,627 --> 00:42:12,460
the easier it can touch people.

904
00:42:12,697 --> 00:42:13,994
The music

905
00:42:14,232 --> 00:42:16,667
was basically guitar,

906
00:42:16,901 --> 00:42:19,734
but I added flute

907
00:42:20,004 --> 00:42:24,703
to the melody.

908
00:42:29,147 --> 00:42:34,881
The clip was U.S. warplanes strafing.

909
00:42:35,186 --> 00:42:37,587
It was a valuable documentary film

910
00:42:37,822 --> 00:42:39,051
because it was in color.

911
00:42:39,323 --> 00:42:43,351
The shot was taken from the plane,
strafing at Taiwan.

912
00:42:44,629 --> 00:42:46,791
Yes, that segment evoked feelings.

913
00:42:47,965 --> 00:42:48,989
Do I sound like I'm bragging?

914
00:42:49,233 --> 00:42:51,668
Inserting my own score and
the film becomes touching?

915
00:42:51,903 --> 00:42:52,631
But to me,

916
00:42:52,870 --> 00:42:55,896
that scene was touching.

917
00:42:56,374 --> 00:42:59,139
Maybe it was the documentary
film itself.

918
00:43:02,246 --> 00:43:04,476
Or maybe,

919
00:43:04,715 --> 00:43:06,843
since I did not experience the era,

920
00:43:07,118 --> 00:43:09,712
when I saw how

921
00:43:09,987 --> 00:43:16,154
my homeland was bombed

922
00:43:16,394 --> 00:43:18,419
I feel

923
00:43:19,797 --> 00:43:24,826
specially sad.

924
00:43:25,837 --> 00:43:28,238
But I never did experience the era,

925
00:43:28,473 --> 00:43:29,907
so I could only use music

926
00:43:30,141 --> 00:43:32,405
to express that feeling.

